ing=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width: 100%;height: auto;display: block;margin: 0 auto;max-height: 50vh\" alt=\"JEE Main 2023 (Online) 24th January Morning Shift Chemistry - Alcohols, Phenols and Ethers Question 61 English Explanation\">","marks":4,"negativeMarks":-1,"topic":"Alcohols, Phenols and Ethers"},{"id":"1l6gqp075","questionNumber":14,"subject":"Chemistry","section":"A","questionType":"MCQ","questionText":"<p>The difference in the reaction of phenol with bromine in chloroform and bromine in water medium is due to :</p>\n\n ","options":["Hyperconjugation in substrate","Polarity of solvent","Free radical formation","Electromeric effect the substrate"],"correctOption":1,"solution":"Phenol gives different products with bromine in\nchloroform and water medium due to the polarity\ndifference between chloroform and water acting as\nsolvent","marks":4,"negativeMarks":-1,"topic":"Alcohols, Phenols and Ethers"},{"id":"m6srn6ae","questionNumber":15,"subject":"Chemistry","section":"A","questionType":"MCQ","questionText":"<p>What amount of bromine will be required to convert 2 g of phenol into 2,4,6-tribromophenol? <br/><br/>(Given molar mass in $\\mathrm{g} \\mathrm{mol}^{-1}$ of $\\mathrm{C}, \\mathrm{H}, \\mathrm{O}, \\mathrm{Br}$ are $12,1,16,80$ respectively )</p>","options":["6.0 g","10.22 g","20.44 g","4.0 g"],"correctOption":1,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1m7es42ny/54b158ed-02a3-42dc-bdf3-ce2a104d5a7e/d54119e0-f053-11ef-a864-2d89966ea2d7/file-jaoe38c1m7es42nz.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1m7es42ny/54b158ed-02a3-42dc-bdf3-ce2a104d5a7e/d54119e0-f053-11ef-a864-2d89966ea2d7/file-jaoe38c1m7es42nz.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"JEE Main 2025 (Online) 23rd January Morning Shift Chemistry - Alcohols, Phenols and Ethers Question 19 English Explanation\"></p>\n<p>$$\\begin{aligned}\n&amp; \\text { Moles of phenol }=\\frac{2}{94}=0.021 \\\\\n&amp; \\therefore \\text { Moles of bromine }=0.021 \\times 3=0.064 \\\\\n&amp; \\therefore \\text { Mass of bromine }=0.064 \\times 160=10.22 \\mathrm{~g}\n\\end{aligned}$$</p>","marks":4,"negativeMarks":-1,"topic":"Alcohols, Phenols and Ethers"}]}